title: Design and Implementation of a Performer Support System for Interactive Visual Performances
title_en: Design and Implementation of a Performer Support System for Interactive Visual Performances
abstract: 本研究はインタラクティブな視覚パフォーマンス向けの実演者支援システムの設計と実装を扱っている。本文献ではPC、カメラ、映像制御装置を中心とするアーキテクチャで実演者用のヘッドマウントディスプレイと観客向け表示を同時に配信する構成を実装し、リアルタイム映像処理によってパフォーマンス表現を拡張する手法を提示している。
abstract_en: This work addresses the design and implementation of a performer support system for interactive visual performances. The paper implements an architecture based on PC, camera, and video control devices to deliver both a head-mounted display for the performer and audience-facing projections in real time to extend performance expression.
positioning_summary: 本研究はインタラクティブな視覚パフォーマンス向けの実演者支援システムの設計と実装という研究領域に位置づけられている。本文献は実演者用ヘッドマウントディスプレイと観客用投影表示を統合して視覚表現を拡張する構成を提示し、PCやカメラ、映像制御装置を組み合わせたアーキテクチャでその位置づけを示している。
positioning_summary_en: This study is positioned in the research area of designing and implementing performer support systems for interactive visual performances. The paper presents an architecture that integrates a head-mounted display for the performer and audience projection displays using PC, camera, and video control devices to extend visual expression.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は実演者がヘッドマウントディスプレイを通じて自身の視覚フィードバックを得ながら同時に観客へ映像提示できる実演者支援システムの実装手法の欠落を埋めることである。本文献はパフォーマーと観客を対象として本システムを実装し、HMDや据え置き表示などの支援手段が操作性や得点に与える影響を明らかにすることを目的としている。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this study is to address the missing implementation methods for a performer support system that allows performers to receive visual feedback via a head-mounted display while presenting images to the audience concurrently. The paper implements the system targeting performers and audiences and aims to clarify how support modalities such as HMD and fixed displays affect operability and task scores.
method_summary: 本研究はPCを中心にカメラ入力と映像制御装置を連携させ、実演者用ヘッドマウントディスプレイと観客向けプロジェクター／スクリーンを同時に駆動する本システムのアーキテクチャを実装している。本文献は一般的なリアルタイム映像処理環境を用いてHMD表示と観客表示の同期を行い、HMD・据え置き表示・支援なしの切替可能な構成で文字探しゲームやボール拾いゲーム、リズムゲームなどの課題を対象にセンサー配置や距離（例：7m、2m、2.7m、HMD視距離約60cm）を取り入れて実装している。
method_summary_en: This study implements a system architecture that integrates PC-based camera input and video control devices to drive both a performer head-mounted display and audience-facing projector/screen simultaneously. The paper uses a real-time video processing environment to synchronize HMD and audience displays and implements switchable conditions—HMD, fixed display, and no support—applied to tasks such as letter search, ball pickup, and rhythm games with sensor placements and distances (e.g., 7m, 2m, 2.7m, HMD viewing distance approximately 60cm).
evaluation_summary: 本研究はHMD・据え置きディスプレイ・支援なしの三条件で得点を比較する実験を行い、支援の効果を検証する評価を実施している。本文献では参加者が文字探しゲーム、ボール拾いゲーム、リズムゲームの三課題を実施して支援条件ごとの得点差を分析し、参加者による主観評価の平均点は0–5点評価で概ね3.3〜4.1の範囲で示されたと報告している。
evaluation_summary_en: The study conducted experiments comparing three conditions—HMD, fixed display, and no support—to evaluate the effect of support on performance scores. The paper reports that participants performed three tasks (letter search, ball pickup, rhythm game), that the study analyzed score differences across support conditions, and that participant subjective ratings on a 0–5 scale averaged approximately 3.3–4.1.

Title: Design and Implementation of a Performer Support System for Interactive Visual Performances
Authors: Jun Ikeda, Tsutomu Terada, Masahiko Tsukamoto, Yoshinari Takegawa
Year: 2009
Abstract: This work addresses the design and implementation of a performer support system for interactive visual performances. The paper implements an architecture based on PC, camera, and video control devices to deliver both a head-mounted display for the performer and audience-facing projections in real time to extend performance expression.
Positioning Summary: This study is positioned in the research area of designing and implementing performer support systems for interactive visual performances. The paper presents an architecture that integrates a head-mounted display for the performer and audience projection displays using PC, camera, and video control devices to extend visual expression.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this study is to address the missing implementation methods for a performer support system that allows performers to receive visual feedback via a head-mounted display while presenting images to the audience concurrently. The paper implements the system targeting performers and audiences and aims to clarify how support modalities such as HMD and fixed displays affect operability and task scores.
Method Summary: This study implements a system architecture that integrates PC-based camera input and video control devices to drive both a performer head-mounted display and audience-facing projector/screen simultaneously. The paper uses a real-time video processing environment to synchronize HMD and audience displays and implements switchable conditions—HMD, fixed display, and no support—applied to tasks such as letter search, ball pickup, and rhythm games with sensor placements and distances (e.g., 7m, 2m, 2.7m, HMD viewing distance approximately 60cm).
Evaluation Summary: The study conducted experiments comparing three conditions—HMD, fixed display, and no support—to evaluate the effect of support on performance scores. The paper reports that participants performed three tasks (letter search, ball pickup, rhythm game), that the study analyzed score differences across support conditions, and that participant subjective ratings on a 0–5 scale averaged approximately 3.3–4.1.
